text: I wonder why whenever a trailer for a DC movie comes out, the fans start bashing Marvel and saying DC is going to crush them. Marvel fans do the same thing to DC fans when a Marvel movie trailer comes out. I think people should stop being "Marvel fans", or "DC fans". Why can't people just like both companies and enjoy all of their movies? Why do people always want to rush and criticize the other movies? Everybody should remember that a movie isn't good just because it's better than another company's movie. It's an amazing time for comic book fans, from both Marvel and DC alike (after all, both of them make awesome movies). Let's not ruin that by creating unnecessary rivalry.

The producers made a bold and necessary decision. ¬†Whether it works out or not remains to be seen.

text: I know I will piss off a lot of people by saying this but this movie looks way too dark! I just can't take it serious. It looks like It's trying to be this thriller with dark and gritty psychopaths teaming up but I don't think it works. I think you should watch a superhero movie for fun and not because you want the "heroes" to morally question their actions and other deep stuff. Thats a huge issue I think DC has. Kids have always been looking up to superheroes and I think the filmmakers were too when they were kids. But now as they have grown older they want to make a more "grown up" movie so the older generation still can enjoy it. But what about the kids now? They are going to get confused by these movies and forget them faster than you can say Infinity War. Superman and Batman are in my opinion THE best superheroes and all is waisted in a big dark Universe where they are both cold-blooded killers. When I heard about a Suicide Squad movie starring Will Smith, I got hyped. I imagined it being a bunch of hardcore criminals wisecracking and just hated each other but had to work together, in a fun way. Well I guess you can't get everything you want.

text: People always assume that the Heath joker is as darkest as it can get but I disagree, heaths joker was strangely philosophical and acted more intelligent than savage- I do understand that my perception of savage and intelligent may vary but hear me out / one of the reasons batman is constantly on the back foot is because joker is unpredictable, heaths joker actually says that he doesn't follow a plan, yet he tries to prove a point to batman that everyone can be corrupted, and that fighting for a city is a lost cause  ( which is a full 180 on what he just said, joker wouldn't turn people to savages for a point: he'd do it for fun) however if we get a selfish and random joker, with r rated brutality: then I think we have a full joker, the exact yang to batman. Joker ain't meant to be smart or raise stakes to insane levels (like when he destroys metropolis in injustice), his life is batman, and batman only. Now if this joker is obsessive over batman then I will forget the tats - this guy could be amazing

text: I can't wait for these DC movies to get underway. What many people don't realize is that the DC movies will help refresh the genre. Don't get me wrong, the Marvel movies have been massively successful and Antman will follow suit no doubt but let's be real. The Marvel movies all follow the same formula/feel/tone. That's why people are increasingly clamoring for the edgier heroes like Punisher, Moon Knight, and Daredevil. I'm ready for a new feel, one that hasn't been felt since the Dark Knight trilogy; call it "dark" if you will. I really don't care. The genre needs both kinds of tones in their movies to flourish or we'll get burnt out.

Considering one of the leads is Harley Quinn and the antagonist is the Joker, it'd be kind of criminal if they didn't.  THIS is what a superhero movie should be. Fun.

text: All these people bashing/doubting Leto obviously have no knowledge/background in acting and/or theatre in general. The man has an Oscar. They don't just give those out for no reason, y'know. Nicholson nailed the circus gag-trick Joker, Ledger nailed the deep, philosophical Joker, and now Leto IS going to nail the (honestly) most difficult Joker of all, the genuinely psychotic one. Idk if the movie will be phenomenal, we'll have to wait and see (and no, it won't be as good as TDK, nothing in the MCU or the DCCU will be as good as TDK). But Leto WILL be phenomenal in it, as will Robbie and Davis at the very least. Everyone needs to just relax. It was the same shit when Ledger was first cast, everyone was enraged. If Leto's Joker isn't as good as Ledger's, it'll be because the film itself isn't as good as TDK, and not because of Leto.

text: not on either side with a lot of the 'who plays the 'best Joker' debate, now questioning Jared Leto taking on the character.¬† but i do think Heath Ledger did an amazing job with the role.¬† and also, i prefer the Joker to have the 'Glasgow smile'... i think it works perfectly with Joker's personality...¬† it is when he can't NOT have a 'permanent smile', which makes him so much more interesting, including how much of his past has affected him...¬† even when he does something awful, that smile is there, and i think it is meant to blur what chaos/destruction and inhumanity he genuinely shows with the times he truly just enjoys the destruction (real smile), VS. when he commits atrocities as a means to an end (permanent fake smile). ¬† the character has so much depth.¬† like i said i have no problem with Jared Leto, but i haven't seen him attempt this kind of character before...¬† and sorry, the trailer pieces of him just dont make you feel that (unexplainable) feeling when you see him.¬† i know i have not watched it all, i would have to reserve my opinion until then.¬† but it doesn't excite me.¬† of¬† course i only really know what a good friend and i talked about¬† (he DID know every comic store/detail of that realm) and how much he explained to me.¬† so forgive me if i am off on something.

text: The trailer was alright, but I'm still not completely sold on this movie. I get that they want to make this movie more serious, but the creepy, slow song and the dramatic lines just make it way too dark; It's the Suicide Squad, after all, it's not supposed to be slow or tragic, it's supposed to be crazy and over-the-top. And Jared Leto's Joker still just looks like a street thug, and not the manipulative super-villain he's supposed to be. I'm not gonna jump of the bandwagon and hate on the movie - I haven't even seen it yet, after all - but I'm not quite sure I like the direction they're going with.

text: I loved ALL the Jokers so far. Even Jim Carrey's (sp?) riddler wasn't horrible imo. So I'm obviously open minded. I am NOT one who criticized Heath's casting. Leto is truly an amazing actor, and I think he's got the chops for it, but no one can honestly say either way until the film comes out. All this bashing and "predicting" is immature.¬†  I read some of the dc comics as a kid, pushing 40 now that's been a LONG time ago. When I heard about the Joker having a skinned face as a mask, I lol'd and just shrugged it off. So I accept there's many adaptations of the Joker now so, bring it on! But the rest? Eh, Harley is NOT the Quinn I know and used to, but than again, my referencing is limited, as compared to the "Fanboys", ya know? So I'm thankful we got that sexy Margot! AND I think she's got some acting chops herself... The rest? I'm just learning about, like Deadshot, the Lizard guy etc, lol. So I guess thankfully, a lot of this mess is new to me, so we'll all see. Will I be first in town with ticket? Most likely. :)¬†  Good or bad, I'm always eager to find out on films like this. Love Batman, now we have BvS, all these other films, we got STAR WARS coming too, jesus man, my heart can't take the anticipation to find out who's doing the best film!

author: Jotaro Kujo

text: A lot of people directed me to this trailer when I said that "Jared Leto's joker looks terrible". So I'm just going to leave my thoughts: (Note, I will only be giving my opinion on the characters I care about, so to those random readers who actually read this, I didn't forget characters, I just have less care for them).¬†  Well, here I am, now seeing this trailer... And I must say, my opinion on this Joker has stayed the same. If anything it improved a very tiny bit, but I still cannot view this as a good Joker yet. To huge Joker fans, and after Heath Ledger's amazing performance, Jared Leto has a lot to go up against, and so far he isn't impressing me. Lets also not forget to throw in the recent performances of Mark Hamill as the Joker in the Arkham games. Jared Leto is failing to impress me, and I found the TV show's (Gotham) Joker to be much better (Cameron Monaghan). I am looking forward to seeing more of Cameron, than of Jared. My faith in this movie role of the Joker is still on edge, but I will try to not cast it aside until I am sitting in the movie theater and reacting with other fans.¬†  This Harley Quinn (Margot Robbie) is sexy as hell. But I actually find myself asking if this sexy is too much for the character. While I do like to see the sexy side of Harley Quinn, I'd really like to see them not turn her into eye candy and nothing more. However, from this trailer I really like the look Margot Robbie gives to Harley Quinn. The outfit looks amazing, the attitude seems crazy enough, and I am looking forward to seeing the character in action. While I have my worries, I also feel this could be an amazing Harley Quinn Performance.¬†  As a huge fan of Will Smith, I have nothing negative to say here. I feel he'll make a good Deadshot. Though I do have to question if Will Smith's voice fits the scene, I don't know, Will Smith has always had a better voice when playing a hero.¬†  Killer Croc looks great. Last I heard it was all make-up, and not CGI. So I have to note that, because if that is the case the make-up crew out did themselves.¬†  As for the over all plot (which I know from the comics), I was already hyped for this. I am looking forward to the plot, and seeing the villains take the reigns as the forefront in the DC movies. Too many movies about super heroes gets boring.

text: I honestly wasn't very on board with this film originally. The on set photos and all of the characters simply looked too cosplayish, bit seeing them in this trailer. I don't know, it kinda fits. This doesn't look like the comic, I doubt it ever will... but it's not bad. It looks like, if anything, it'll be a good action flick, and I'm okay with that. You'll never fully capture the feeling of a comic, no matter how hard you try. The only one to truly get close would be Watchmen, and even then it failed to do so entirely. So yeah, I'm a bit pumped to see this. Jared Leto, while not looking the part (that "Damaged" on the forehead still annoys me), definitely looks like he has the act down pat. So I'm pumped.

text: Personally, I'm very excited about Leto's Joker. Don't get me wrong, Ledger was good, but he didn't seem like the comic book Joker to me. Leto's has the bleached skin, bright green hair, red lips, and looks and sounds scary. Ledger was more of a goofy anarchist, where as Leto is a straight forward psychopathic nutcase.   As for the tattoos and teeth, they make sense, and are clearly to emphasize that he's been in business for a while. Batman knocked his teeth out, and the tattoos are due to his time in prison, doing what joker does and decorating himself. Not just clothes, but ink.  The forehead tat is so great, because if someone got that in real life they would be referring to emotional damage. He's physically damaged. Dunked in a chemical bath, beaten, and scarred. It's all a joke to him!

text: People complaining about Harley...c'mon cant we be happy that we FINALLY get to see her character in a full length hollywood movie? So you didnt hear her say puddin'? Looks like this movie will be taking place before, possibly during the early stages, of her becoming acquainted with Joker. We might not hear her say that word till later in the franchise. And also that she doesnt have the annoying high pitched voice? Look at Batman, a character known for his voice....in ALL movies his voice was different. Superman killed someone in Man of Steel *gasps* oh no they strayed from the cartoon and comic adaptation of characters. Honestly I would rather them stray from that than the plot and storyline. As long as this follows according to the plot, Harley could be a latin redhead who speaks nothing but spanish and I wouldnt care, as long as she played her role in the Squad....lol okay maybe not that much difference but you get my point. I think her character will end up going over well. I predict she will be the new favorite bad girl in cinema, much like Bellatrix Lestrange was. Teen girls actually looked up to Bellatrix, though she was bad. Same thing will happen with Harley :) she will be why I go see this movie.

text: I'm getting bad vibes from this new Joker. ¬†Way too psycho looking; even more so than Heath Ledger's Joker which, I'm sure most people would agree, is the best Joker so far and is almost impossible to top. ¬†The Joker character is essentially a clown, albeit an extremely clever and dangerous one, but nevertheless, a clown. ¬†Too much psychosis makes the character so menacing it undermines his seemingly benign silliness which he uses to conceal his true nature as a criminal genius. ¬†I have to admit, I felt the same way about Heath Ledger prior to watching the Dark Knight, then wound up being blown away by his kick ass performance. ¬†I hope I'm wrong in this assessment of Jared Leto's version, so I'll wait until the movie comes out. ¬†Who knows, I might be pleasantly surprised.

text: I refuse to judge a film before it has come out, but I don't think it's really possible to adequately develop so many characters in 2/2.5 hours. I mean, this is introducing and has to develop:  Deadshot Harley Quinn Amanda Waller CADMUS (Possibly) Joker Killer Croc Katana Captain Boomerang Whoever the skull guy is (Black Mask?) Whoever else they have in it.  Really, with just those 8 characters, they are going to have to skip over A LOT of backstory and motivation. I think that this film would work better if it came after all of these characters were developed by stand-alone films. That's why Avengerse works, because they didn't have to waste time developing the characters and instead, could focus solely on the story, the action and the relationships between the characters.  I'm not saying that it CAN'T work this way around, i'm just saying that DC is going have to rely heavily on the audience being familiar with all of these characters to begin with, if they want to be able to do this crossover well.

text: Huge fan of DC comics especially Batman, Joker, Harley ETC. If you are like me you will be a bit worried. I really hope they don't ruin it. I like the look of Harley, Margot good choice really pretty and hanging in the cage cause of her gymnastic ability,  really liked that but her voice isn't what I expected and part of me thought they would pay more of a homage to the red n black ensemble but hey its not my vision. They have her dark/crazy/sexy side down but I just hope they get her smart sense of humour too. killer Croc and enchantress look great and obvious choice for Waller no doubt. Unsure about smith being Deadshot. He's a great actor so he may surprise us being a bad-ass and hopefully they capture Boomerang/Deadshot banter. Joker Emm still on the fence with that one not sure at all, I cant really make a judgement only seeing 10 seconds or so. The voice sounds creepy but the laugh isn't as manic as id of liked. I get there kinda going for the suave fresh faced look of the joker in the 'dark knight returns' but give me 'The killing joke' or BMTAS type of joker any day of the week. Just my opinion. I'm still mega excited been waiting to long. Looks good and really, really looking forward to it. Obviously we've only seen 3 mins. I suppose we will have to wait and see. Cant believe we have to wait till next yr¬†damn it . :)

text: I'm sorry to say this, but Will Smith really looks like the weak link here. we know that he doesn't do well out of his comfort zone, and playing a villain is far outside that comfort zone. looking at the trailer it seems like they wrote the character to suit him, rather than writing an accurate depiction of the character from the comics. cuz Deadshot is a villian no question, but here he looks to be written as more of a sympathetic antihero type. then there's the big problem with Smith's ego. I bet if any other actor was playing the character, he would be wearing the mask most of the time. but it's Will Smith, so we have to see his face most of the time right? what are they gonna do? make a movie where he's actually playing a different type of character, one who usually wears a mask? what are you nuts? plus in the trailer he gets more lines than almost every other member of the team, most of them don't even get dialog. Will Smith does though, and he gets one-liners too. I doubt it's a coincidence.

text: It literally PAINS me to see all of these Leto haters talking about how "bad" of a Joker he's going to be. If we're gonna be real about it, the worst Joker ever was Jack Nicholson. And I'm not saying that because he was bad, by any means. He was just the worst. The Joker is a hard character to portray, and each actor that's been in those shoes has played him differently. Personally, I like the up-to-date maniacal take he seems to be letting through. That laugh is eerily reminiscent of Mark Hamill, in a way. And regarding his scene in this trailer: the torturing: very Heath Ledger-esque. So before you start railing on Leto, just remember that he didn't write this particular Joker. He was handed this character, and I'm sure he will do outstanding.

text: Dumb comment section. plenty of IQ's lower than a five year olds on display. -If you mention "Marvel vs DC" then grow up, they are comics end of story, enjoy them or dont. Arguing over them is the most braindead thing ever (unless your under 10) -If you mention "ledger's joker vs leto's joker"- go read up on the thousand different ways the joker has been done in comics, animted series, films etc. He is a very¬†malleable and versatile character who usually is played acording the world he inhabits (ledgers one only worked in nolans world etc) -If you compare this with Batman vs Superman - why ? they are totally different films except for the fact that they are DC comic characters.¬† - If you think heath ledger's performance as joker was "the greatest performance in a movie ever" then you dont watch many films or understand much about acting. It was very good although not particularly difficult - joker is a very easy character to play for an actor - an actors dream. Much harder to play realistic characters or people that dont wear everything (tell the audience everything) on the outside. Lots of fun to play though.

text: Ok before i say this i just want to clarify that i am a HUGE fan of Heath Ledgers joker, and that performance for me made the entire movie such an enjoyable experience. Everybody is saying that the joker is being portrayed wrong by Leto, or that he could never live up to Ledgers manifestation of the character, but i'll tell you what after seeing this clip alone, i'm pretty pumped for his incarnation already. To me he looks like the joker's personality.¬†He looks sick, sadistic and creepy. At the end of the day is that not what the joker is about? A reckless psychopath with a sick sense of humour? Also i kinda like the tattoos and crowns on the teeth. It makes him look like he's been antagonizing batman for a long time and also adds a slightly modern twist with the addition of tattoos. Almost like he's tryna put on a show and get attention (yet another trait of the character... just saying)

text: This Joker seems a lot more like the Comic Joker than Heath Ledger did to be honest. He was great for the Nolanverse dont get me wrong. Really his Joker was a surprisingly political anarchist type villain. He would play games of chance like "who will you save? Harvey or Rachel?" Which boat will blow up?? This is fun!" He gave a big anarchy speach to Two-Face and practically jizzed his pants when Harvy put a gun to his head and flipped a coin to decide weather or not to pull the trigger. But we never saw him to be the type to torture and kill just for his own sick pleasure. It was always a game or a political statement. This Joker (and the comic Joker) seem to be more evil and tourturous. Like "im not playing games of chance here. I just want to hurt and torture and kill because its fun and I get sick pleasure from inflicting pain and suffering onto others". Two different Jokers. I dont think Heath's sly smart and cunning Joker would work as well as a purly evil deranged psychopath. And im very much looking forward to this one.¬†  Thanks for reading.

text: I'm a huge fan of Marvel, like I have a bunch of Marvel comics, so don't get me wrong, I'm trying not to be biased here. I know a lot about DC but I prefer Marvel over DC. So if I sound biased I'm sorry: I think this movie looks kinda bad. It doesn't look HORRIBLE, but it isn't the greatest thing DC has made. I feel they could've done a lot more with this movie. Judging by the trailer this is after the Superman V Batman movie. I think what the should've done is put this before the Man of Steel movie, so in a way it's a double prequel. It's a prequel to Man of Steel in a sort, and it's also showing what Batman has gone up against in the past. Also the Joker looks absolutely horrible. There's no topping Heath Ledger's Joker, but even with his Joker out of the picture, this isn't the best. But that's just on looks. Also what's up with giving Killer Croc a nose?! He doesn't have a nose! Well, I know he has a nose, but they didn't even TRY to make it reptilian like. Also, I'm not trying to compare DCCU to the MCU, but I think the DCCU is making a big mistake not having Arrow and The Flash be in the DCCU. So far just by the trailer, if I had to compare this to a Marvel movie it'd have to be the MCU's Hulk. That forgotten movie that's in the $5 bin at Wal-Mart but is somehow still in the MCU :/.

text: Damn it, again?!? Why skinny Waller? What's wrong with fat Waller? Why does Hollywood hate fat Waller so much huh? They did in in Green lantern, and then the Arrow show and now here too. Fat Waller is my favorite black comic character. Bar none. Skinny Waller isn't shit.  Oh well, doesn't matter. While some of the other castings are almost just as bad, Will Smith as Deadshot is a total deal breaker for me. Doesn't look a thing like Dead Shot without that mask on. "We some kina Suici Squat". Lol nope! Gonna pass on paying to see this one. Thank god for them innernetz tho.  Between Age of Ultron, every Fantastic Four, the last Spider-Man movie and anything DC has done since Nolan started butchering the Batman Universe, it seems like Hollywood has finally put the final nails in the coffin of my childhood. Since the first Iron Man film, comic adaptations have been the last bit of Hollywood drivel I bothered to consume. Entirely for the nostalgia factor. They're not even pretending to cast actors who look anything like their comic counterparts anymore in most cases. And because of that, the nostalgia factor is gone. It was a better run than I expected in all honesty, though!  Oh well, still got my comics! Well at least the old ones, lol. New stuffs kind of the same PC-pandering propaganda as the movies are becoming.

text: That's the thing I've always marveled about DC characters.... get it?¬† Never mind.  Anyways when you look at a DC character, on the surface they look simple.¬† But when you look deep down they are far more complex, and you see it along their journey for both the good guys and the bad guys.  Even though this Joker looks like a crackhead clown, the way he says, "I'm just going to hurt you, really, REALLY, bad," you can see how much he enjoys the suffering as though he's feasting off of it like Vlad Dracul when he has portraits of him having dinner while watching his impaled victims struggle as they die slowly and painfully.  Superman going from a sheltered child, to a drifter trying to find his own way, to becoming the world's greatest superhero with his path now clear.  And of course Batman who needs no introduction.

text: Lot of haters out there. The trick to enjoying these kind of movies is to understand that directors take artistic liberties to complete their vision. I for one am very interested to see how this joker pans out. Heaths joker was absolutely enthralling to me. A dark, dark character that emphasized on anarchy. A truly wicked man who wanted to watch the world burn. Letos joker seems to be a character that leans towards a sphyco that really enjoys himself. More light hearted. Not comparable by any means if you ask me. Oranges and apples.

text: I think the the look for the Joker in this film is different which is why it's going to be good. His look is a lot more modernized and Gothem-esque. Previous jokers (no diss to them or their acting, all were phenomenal) looked like simple people with clown makeup. Remember that this is a movie that takes place years after the Joker is incarcerated, so over time his look will change with how prison changes him. This look is refreshing & up to date, and just from the trailer, Leto already seems like he's going to do a good job playing the part. Keep an open mind for the movie. I also think that waiting till the end of the trailer to show him was smart.

text: This trailer does not inspire confidence in me. Remove the haunting music and imagine more realistic sound for the scenes they show. It's mostly explosions, gunshots, and crashes. Not that there's anything necessarily wrong with that, it's just that they seem to be banking on the action rather than the characters. Speaking of which, I can almost guarantee you the only two characters that are going to be even remotely interesting are Deadshot and Harley, since they're the only high profile villains in the linup aside from the Joker, and frankly, both of them are B-listers at best. There's also suspiciously little dialogue, which makes me think back to the main problem with MOS; solid directing and acting, but awful dialogue and a nonsensical plot. Finally, and I'm sure most of you have already realized this, but they're trying too hard to be dark and edgy, especially when it comes to the Joker. A movie that takes itself too seriously usually either becomes funny for the wrong reasons or just plain doesn't work. That's why MCU movies work so well, even the 'bad' ones. They manage to stay more lighthearted,  which actually makes people more emotionally invested in the characters and the movie itself. Which brings me to the root of the problem: DC seems to be under the impression that dark=realistic, which is just not true.

text: The problem is everyone have they own opinion... but you can't say SHIT until you see the movie, if you don't like how he looks fine.. but don't forget Jared Leto is an outstanding and incredible actor and he will definitely put a lot of hard work to a character like The Joker... I mean The Joker is the most famous Villain everybody knows him, and obviously he needs to make sure he will impress those people with his joker style. To me personally his tattoos are fine , I mean don't forget the joker is a pshychopath and a maniac , he is capable of anything and I saw a lot of people complain about his grills , like you know the batman loves to beat the living crap out of The Joker , so it kinda obvious why he has grills. Other thing I want to add , is that his Joker is more like a comic joker when Heath's joker is more realistic one. There is different incarnations to the joker , I mean so many. For example in Death of the family comic book he actually cuts his face and glues it back on his face and apparently he also sticks his face which he cuts on the wall to prove a point to the batman. So The Joker is capable of anything , he is a crazy mental person don't forget about that. To me this Joker looks much more better then Jack Nicholson's or Heath Ledgers , and personally just maybe Leto will prove that his Joker performance is the one to remember forever even in HUNDRED YEARS TIME. I mean we all going to remember Heath's great performance and Jack's as well but I think Leto will set the bar high, I think by the look of the trailer his acting and his voice is incredible , I mean his voice reminds me a bit of Mark Hamils as well , to me he looks like a PERFECT JOKER. So I think we will see something incredible in The Suicide Squad film.

text: This looks like it will be very Harley focused. That end bit where we see the Joker is probably some kind of flash back where he tortures her and in that way turns her into something akin to himself. Which means that we will be expected to accept her as a good person in actuality and that the crimes she has commited has been beyond her control. Now that sounds pretty damn interesting. She is already an interesting character, it is just that few choose to explore her. Harley is often portrayed as the scandally dressed antagonist who blindly follows and doesn't think for herself. Here she is made unattractive via makeup and costume which will allow the actress to give a good performance and the film to explore her character in depth. It removes the sexualition and objectification of the character. Which is actually quite exciting. Although DC is trying to follow in Marvels footsteps with a cinematic universe at least they are taking a new direction with their properties, which in turn makes the films look all the more appealing. Say what you will about the Joker and his visual style but at least they are trying something new and creative. Hey ,he probably won't be the real Joker anyway and instead we will get a another well developed character. Batman v Superman doesn't look very exciting with the over abundance of CGI and action scenes, so this movie will really have to make up for it. So far it doesn't look too bad, at least that is for something which falls into the 'superhero' genre.

text: everything wrong with this trailer  1: it depressing. the music and how its constantly fading in and out is depressing. when it should have some awesome instrumentals playing and showing how awesome the action is. not how sad its making us. not every dc film has to look like Nolan North or Zack Snyder's (who i honestly think hate bright or even semi-bright colors)  2: ¬†killer croc and katana replacing black spider and king shark. i don't understand why when they didn't need to be. i don't know¬†who katana is but i do think killer croc would have benefited more in a batman movie as a supervillain.  3: the joker. I'm sorry Jared Leto¬†but right now you're coming off as just a crazy person to me and not someone who can outwit and even trade blows with batman and be his archenemy for decades.  4: Harley Quinn. the absolute worst aspect of this entire film. and its not just this movies fault its how she's been protruded in comics for the past several years. she's not even close to wearing her original costume; the animated movie at least had the decency to put her in something similar. for some reason writer and artist seem to think Harley's badassness and sexiness can only be achieved through her wear as little clothing and as far away from her original costume as possible. but besides that the worst part is her personality. if you've ever read her solo comic before the reboot, or better yet seen batman the animated series¬†you know¬†she didn't start out crazy but developed it through¬†her love of the joker...and she's totally aware of this. she knows she's crazy and cant go back to a normal life and she accepts this, but she's not completely deprived of human decency either. this Harley just doesn't seem to be all there. she seems to have some sort of mental illness more of a destructive¬†bipolar disorder than just enjoying anarchy like her boss/lover. but there are plenty of reasons why Harley is so popular¬†and this iteration is certainly not one of them.

text: What a time to be alive. Hell 10-15 years ago a lot of the comic book movies that came out were "meh" movies at best. But with that being said, its times like these I love being fans of both Marvel and DC and not having to take sides like a lot of silly people do. And as one of the top comments says, them having completely different moods to them makes it so much more enjoyable (no burnouts) but also makes Marvel and DC incomparable.  Personally, I love the witty, sarcastic, humor side to the Marvel movies. Thats kind of the vibe I got reading the comics whereas the DC comics always kind of had the darker tone. Nolans Batman trilogy, regardless if its not in this cinematic universe, definitely set the tone for the current DCCU.¬†  All that being said, I definitely have my issues with this movie. For one, I think Will Smith was a horrible casting choice. I obviously still have a ton of faith in this movie, but even in his two scenes in this I get the sense everything he says and does will be corny and cheesy as hell. I'm also not totally sold on this Joker character. I think Leto was a perfect casting choice, and he's more than capable of performing the Joker that they want, I'm just not sure that they Joker they want is the right one. So far, I'd say people are split just from what I've seen, and you can't judge it from one sentence in the first trailer, but from the set photos of him dressing like he's going to a night club and driving a pimped out Lamborghini the tattoos and the grills, I'm just not completely sold on what theyre trying to achieve with this Joker especially when he looks like a junky meth head.

text: This trailer really made me think about things. The seconds after the jokers scene really got to me. They made me think of a childhood memory. A memory which begins with me sitting in the corner of an alley in my hometown. I remember I looked out onto the street. I saw people walking. They were walking in an odd manner. A manner which deeply bothered me. It got to me on a psychological level. It was intense. It was full of life. It was everything I was missing. It was the essence of who we are as beings. It was a rhythmic series of movements set to a beat. A beat from a song. This movement was dance. Strange and beautiful. I never forgot. And from that day forward I decided to bring a little of that strange and beautiful to my YouTube channel. And so, please check it out if you can.

text: So I originally posted this as a reply to someone else in the comics but I decided I'd rather just post it like this.¬†After watching this trailer twice¬†I am...concerned. Deep down I really want this movie to do well, and¬†I kind of¬†think it will. I always loved the Suicide Squad and again for this movie I have high hopes. However, this is what scares me: This will be the first ever live action movie featuring Harley Quinn. Now from this preview I think the role will be just fine and can handle any criticisms that may follow the movie for her character (again this is from just the trailer). Ok, second, the Joker. We've seen A LOT of different incarnations of the Joker and in present times the biggest incarnations are Mark Hamill and Heath Ledger. Now I don't know much about Jared Leto, but I have to say I am concerned with what I saw in the trailer, not really in the voice or lines we heard because those were good, but I can't buy the appearance. Don't get me wrong, I'm intrigued by this gritty look, but the teeth? And all the tattoos including the "J" on his face? Sorry but to me that's not Joker, it's a wannabe by my interpretation, and that's what concerns me. I'm afraid I won't be able to believe his particular performance and the rest of the movie will crash with him. Maybe it won't, but if Leto can't pull off the Joker like this trailer is leaving me to believe he can't, I think it will crash and not be good and that disappoints me.

text: In this film joker is not supposed to be young he has been fighting batman for years and has many scars, etc from doing so. His metal teeth are also not grills. They are metal plates used to fill in the broken teeth from fighting batman. if you look closely you see how some of the teeth transitiion into metal with uneven edges along the teeth as if they are filling in the ends of broken teeth. In addition, the joker has had tatoos before in comics and the ones they have given leto's joker are actually much cooler than what he has had. And with regards to the fan theory it is neat how ever i feel it would only work in a comic. On the big screen it might be hard to believe joker turning adult batman instructed jason todd into a new joker because of his personality traits and morale code. The most the joker was really ever able to do to todd was make him hate batman whichled into the redhood ordeal, but again jason did not turn into a maniac after his totrue from joker just a darker vigilante with a looser morale code

text: I won't lie, I clicked this trailer because I saw Jared Leto portraying The Joker, which isn't surprising. he did a wonderful job in Dallas Buyer's Club, and I wasn't surprised he beat out Jonah Hill for the best supporting actor award. But, then my attention was diverted to the comments where I kept seeing "Heath Ledger" and The Dark Knight, and how misinformed this younger generation apparently is.   Heath Ledger studied the original Joker character, which is Jack Nicholson. I'm not at all shocked that most of you don't know that, probably wasn't born yet when the original batman came out (1989). I even remember going to see it at the movies with my mom. That Joker was a little on the comedic side, but Heath reinvented the character, making him more sinister in Nature by studying the personality profile of the Joker, not the funny character Jack portrayed in 89, which led to Heath's untimely death sadly. Jared is just continuing that persona and just from the trailer, he did a wonderful job.   As for Jared, also keep seeing thirty seconds to mars. Yes, he is the front man for that group with his brother, but that wasnt his "big break". What alot of people don't know is Jared has been an actor for a very long time before Thirty seconds to Mars, He started out in the 90's acting, in fact, I saw him for the first time in Black & White (an indie hip hop movie that tackled race and hip hop culture). He also had a small part in Phone Booth (Colin Farrell & Kiefer Sutherland), which was edited out, you only see his part on the DVD extra scenes and he was also in American Psycho. The irony in American Psycho is he was killed off by Patrick Bateman, who was played by Christian Bale, who then went on to do the Dark Knight series.   I'm just an old school movie lover. And Jared has come such a long way, he will be the Johnny Depp of this generation. He takes the edgy roles and keeps his sanity in the process, and that's a skill not very many in show business has.

I mean face tattoo's and grills are kind of ''fashionable'' and ''cool'' now, but in 20 years, it will look like a bad cliche. Same goes for El Diablo who looks like a Zombie Boy ripoff. Zombie Boy is kind of a cultural icon, or was, since he's been in a Lady's Gaga video but people will forget about him or already has. It feels like the direction went for a bling bling look, and what is bling bling right now, won't be in a couple of years. One of the thing I liked the most about Nolan's trilogy is that they did not go overboard on anything. It will always look good and be a masterpiece superhero trilogy. Anyway, I hope that at least the movie will be good.

text: While I will agree that this Joker is much more in the comic book world here. In my personal opinion & theory, I still don't think that comic book Joker would get tattoos. The reason being is that he's a narcissist. He already thinks that he is perfect just the way he is. So why would he get tattoos and metal teeth and possibly compromise his perfection?  While I am aware that there is a comic book Joker with a tattoo on his back, the author of that story arc has always taken characters out on a limb and made them a little different... Also, the Joker may be crazy but he's still a classy guy. Even Ledger's Joker, while he was more edgy and raw, was still pretty classy! (e.g. Pushed back hair and purple suit) So, for those reasons, I could personally do without all the modifications.   However, all that being said, this is THIS world's version of the Joker! And I am excited to see what Leto can do!

Harley and the way she is acting in the trailer just makes her seem very bland to me. Joker's one joke towards the end didn't feel like his character. It was one of those attempted Joker jokes that just ended badly. Not saying the actors are bad, it's just I don't think the director or the actors are going to pull off the necessary parts to this movie dealing with each character. I could be wrong and I hope this movie proves itself to me that it won't leave me in disappointment.

text: People tend to judge quickly before the movie is even out. If we remember correctly Heath Ledger had quite a few negative remarks made toward him for taking on the role of the Joker in The Dark Knight returns. After the movie was released and people saw it, then people fell in love with his role. The point is each Joker actor has done well to this point:  - Cesar Romero was a funny Joker in the 60s series which fit the part - Jack Nickolson was a flamboyant Joker with the right attitude to play the role in the 1989 movie - Heath Ledger was a psychotic twisted Joker for the 2008 movie   - Jared Leto ???????????  Time will tell on how Leto plays this role and if he fits the movie just right. However with three successors before him who played the part well, I believe Leto could be in good company IF he does this right. The last thing we need is a bad Joker actor to haunt us for years to come (bad enough we had George Clooney ruin Batman for a short time).

text: I'm assuming this is going to be PG13 right? I say that only because the studio recently said they were aiming for 700 million to be grossed from this flick. That kind of money mostly only comes from PG13 or lower (it's a rare occasion for something rated higher to draw such numbers, and it's only happened for "cinematic events" far larger than this. For them to assume they could draw such money from a higher rating would be the kind of gamble big movie studios don't make). Also, because it's part of the DC shared universe I doubt they are going to let one film stick out like a sore thumb years from now (we know they are aiming for PG13 for their main superhero flicks, it was already confirmed for BvS).  It's a shame, given all the ridiculous hype about the movie being so dark, Leto so insane, all the actors so scared, therapist brought on site because it was so disturbing etc etc. I guess the best performance of all is that of marketing.

text: My previous prediction for _Suicide Squad_ was this:  A good opening weekend, but a significant decline in the next week, and onwards, resulting in a film that fails to "meet expectations", as the studios like to put it. Among serious fans, it would be considered "disappointing". It will not earn a sequel, Harley Quinn will go back into "development hell", and we may never see Jared Leto up against Batfleck again. That was my earlier prediction. But now, the more I hear about Will Smith and his people getting involved in re-writes to the script, plus what I see in this trailer, I revise my prediction:  *This movie is going to FLOP,* except among the "I'll watch Will Smith in anything" crowd.  If the rumours I'm hearing are at all accurate, Will Smith is insisting on a more central role, and fundamental changes to his character. He's gonna play ruthless assasin Deadshot as yet another "felon with a heart of gold". We already see him hugging a young girl, presumably his daughter, Zoe. (AW, how touching, he's like Ant-Man, except for murdering people!) ' Will Smith is simply too egotistical to play an antihero or flat-out villain.  To make this film into a Will Smith vehicle, they will sacrifice scenes of depth and detail about the Joker/Harley relationship. THE BIGGEST untapped fan base for this movie is the community of fans who idealize the Harley Quinn/Joker relationship, ever since Harley was created in _Batman: The Animated Series_ in the 1990s. If this film does NOT play to that fan base, it will be an artistic and financial failure, and those disappointed, disgusted, outraged, offended fans will spread the word quickly. it's an ensemble film, but at least half the people who plan to attend want to see the Joker and Harley Quinn interact, not more "Let's go save the world" Will Smith cliiches. (See 1:45 - 2:10). So, yeah: I want it to be good, but I expect it to bomb, for good reason. I hope I'm wrong, though.

text: I must admit I was hesitant and apprehensive when I heard leto was to play the joker, the roles he has played recently have all been rather complex. but I look at this trailer and I'm reminded of "Assault On Arkham" where the suicide squad was sent into arkham to retrieve an item and kill the riddles,  the joker escapes and pretty much single handedly screws up the whole operation.  and when I look at this trailer I can see the same thing happening, joker turns up and adds a little chaos. don't get me wrong I loved heath ledgers joker, while similar to the jack Nicholson original, it was an amazing stand alone performance by ledger. now I say this, heath ledger took the role and made it his own, which none of us realised until we saw the whole film. I say to those people slamming leto, give him a chance. yes the look is completely different but he is not trying to copy or emulate heath ledgers joker, he is trying to make his own which is far more difficult. The joker in the comic book has gone through many iterations that have all been unique . so I say bring on this new joker, I'll reserve judgement till after I've seen the film as you all should too

text: This Joker debate is killing me; it's waaaay too freaking early to tell.  Whose Joker will be crazier? Jack Nicholson, who is like already demented by default? Cesar Romero, who was a campy loony clown? Heath, who came completely out of left field on the "pretty boy haters" as a ruthless maniacal mastermind? Or Jared Leto, who acts just as well as he sings, and has the awards to prove he can pull whatever he wants out of his arsenal at a moment's notice? It's just too freaking soon to tell. But I bet he'll do a phenomenal job and creep everyone out. We didn't see much of him at all in this trailer except the bit at the end. So...yeah.  And his teeth are fine -- I think the grill fits the whole punk-dystopian edge Suicide Squad's aesthetic has going for it -- everyone got a new twist to their look, including Harley, who doesn't look at all like her iconic harlequin red and black pantomime renditions like in the cartoons. So they gave the Joker weird teeth -- Heath's Joker looked different from Jack & Caesar's more comic book loyal looks, too.   I'm actually more worried about Will Smith's performance, tbh. Because he's more of a hit or miss actor for me -- sometimes he gives AMAZING performances, like in Happyness and Hancock and Bad Boys, but even then he can fall flat sometimes, or overact so it looks cheesy and fake.

text: I'm going to make a prediction. Slipknot is going to die. Who's Slipknot? He's a Firestorm villain with a rope gimmick who's part of the eponymous squad. Didn't see him in the trailer? That's because he only appears for a split second at 2:25. Every other one of the villains is noticeable and appears a few times in the trailer, but he only appears once. Why?  Let's talk for a second about the Suicide Squad. The team is comprised of super villains who have bombs implanted in them. If they try and run away they get blown up. In the comics Slipknot was part of the team. Then he tried to run and got blown up.  I'm willing to bet the reason he doesn't appear much in the trailer is because at some point during the film he will try to run and be blown up to show off Waller's ruthlessness.

text: so much hate on leto? don't get me wrong, i am not a big fan of him, and at first i was skeptic about him playing the joker... the more information i have, the more i look at the trailer i think i might be wrong and he will be an outstanding joker. (yes, i still don't like him).. people need to move away from the comics and be open to some changes.  but, even in the comics, there are different jokers.. and also why compare leto with ledger? i don't think you should do that, because i think that every joker portrait in movies stands for its own. You can't compare nicholson to Romero, you can't compare ledger to nicholson and you can't compare ledger to leto. different jokers / different movies / different settings.  and i like the cast overall and i am absolutely blown away from harley.  i will not say this movie is going to be shit, nor will i say it is going to the best... i will have to wait for it to come out, watch it and then i can judge about it.  of course, IMO a lot of people ranting about the movie, will go see it, and because they have low expectations in it, they will find all kind of shit to rant about. they will leave and say " i knew it is going to be shit"

text: I, like Jared, always got an "old soul" tone from every Joker. idk how to explain, but it's something out of folklore, or Greek tragedy. he's just got an old sprit about the character. and Jared has clearly encapsulated this trait, with the laugh. it sounds so menacing, and also like the Emperor from Star Wars. pure evil. he is also balancing this out with a 1920s Broadway theatre type charisma that is so interesting to watch. he is so expressive physically, unlike any other Joker(heath was too, but it wasn't as cartoonish) he's so animated as well. also, this is the first time he isn't completely caked with make up, and he does really good face acting to show off his quirkiness.  BTW don't just judge by his appearance, if you were a Joker fan as atleast I am, then you would be analyzing every single piece of footage of Jared as the Joker, and you will already find, even before the movie has come out, that he IS 3 dimensional character, who has all the nuanses of the Joker that we all know and love.  I'm with ya, I hate that promo image, because if you do actually take the time to analyze, it is obviously a TERRIBLE representation of what he will be in the movie.

text: So, this was the tone they were initially going for. However due to poor reception of BvS they panic and added more humors and jokes, trying to make it light hearted. Hence making the movie tonally inconsistent and broken narratives. Seriously, studio executives should just leave the fimmakers make their movies on their own way. Just look at these past movies; Spiderman 3 Amazing Spider man 1 & 2 Fan4stic BvS (Pretty sure it was studio's decision to cram in as many DC characters into 1 movie)  Sure there have been few cases when director had a full control and movie didnt turn out well but generally when it comes to big blockbusters (in this case comic book/super heroes movies) studios should just let the film maker do it on their own way.  I am really sad to hear that this movie is getting poor reception.

text: I watched the movie last night, and I have to say this trailer had all of the scenes in the final cut.  So if anything was changed, maybe they altered the music to emphasize the humorous moments, which were basically Harley Quinn saying crazy stuff.  Either way, the movie would have sucked, it didn't make any sense for this team to even be assembled, when they obviously show that Batman and the Flash were still around to protect everyone.  If those two had been captured, then I would understand the need for creating Suicide Squad, but the whole thing was forced, and they just became pals a little too quickly.  The joker was the biggest let down. It felt like he was channeling a Jim Carrey version of it, like The Mask.  I was waiting for him to do a silly dance.

text: I think it should be said.  No matter what you feel about the movie, or the comic or how ever disappointed or happy you were about this movie, this may be one of the greatest trailers of all time.  Knowing absolutely nothing about DC or comics, or whatever the hell "Suicide Squad" was, this trailer alone made me a fan.  Perfectly done, hooked me and made me excited to see this movie.  But first I had to learn what it was all about.   That alone has to be a total victory for the DC universe.  Now I am a total fan.  And the movie was good.  Most of the world appears to not agree with me, but I don't care.  It was very good.    I am kinda hopeful someone else out there had a similar reaction.  By the way, are there awards for trailers?  This one should probably win something.  But then, I am just some guy on the internet.  Maybe the world disagrees with me on that too.

author: karen Joyce

text: //Rant// This is what happens when studio heads interfere...this was a fantastic trailer, that had a voice, and atmosphere. The last minute reshoots and re-edits screwed up the original vision this movie had. When you squander around trying to cater to what you think people will like, rather than sticking to the original direction...you lose on all fronts. Why hire a director like David Ayer if you're going to smear it all at the last minute? Nolan's films worked because they were headed by a great filmmaker with little interference. Zack Snyder fails not because his movies are too serious, but because they are written badly with style over substance. It's not that people don't want to see gritty/darkness or something. We just want to see it WELL-WRITTEN, and with a committed style.  The studio heads making executive decisions for the DC cinematic universe need to stop scrambling around hoping to get liked, and have the balls to commit to something. Otherwise we have a bunch of half-measures that go nowhere. //End Rant.

text: I was so disappointed at the final cut of this movie that I saw on Monday.  This Comic Con trailer from last year was what got me originally stoked about Suicide Squad. It looked haunting and moving at the same time, a band of misfits uniting to defeat some very bad guys, especially the Joker. I mean, who out there didn't think the Joker was the main villain based on this trailer? The way they saved him until the very end of the movie. The background song.  I was a bit apprehensive when I heard WB execs panicking over the box office results and reviews of Batman vs. Superman and how they were going to tweak it to make it appear more light hearted and humorous. And my apprehensions were correct. The movie was a mess, a mish mash of odd bits and pieces of scenes that never seemed to come together. And there was hardly any Joker in the movie at all!  I suppose one thing that this trailer got right was the ending lines of the song at the end of the trailer, the joke truly was on us.

text: This is probably my favourite trailer ever!  Now I'm going to give my opinion on the film. Quickly.  Rushed. A mess. Unorganised. Leto was OK as the joker. It would have been better if he wasn't such a big part of the marketing and promotion. Or if he just had a small cameo at the end or something. Leto's acting was good but the joker was written as this cool gangster/mob boss. I don't want that. I want to be terrified of the joker. I want him to be maniacal. Unpredictable. And chaotic. The seen in which Dr. Harleen Quinzel jumps into the tub of acid and 'becomes' Harley Quinn was done wrong.  Enchantress is useless as the antagonist. Either have joker as the antagonist or not have him in the film at all (like I said earlier).  The bar scene was good. The way the introduced the 'squad' was good. Especially deadshot (whom will smith portrayed brilliantly).  Overall the film was too cartoony and fast paced and less eerie like it was initially going to be until DC had bad reception with

text: So I just finished reading the official movie novelisation, which was based on the original script and cut of the film, and I can say that it was 100% better than the butchered final product. The original cut was definitely darker and grittier, but it was supposed to be, because the film is about a bunch of murderers and psychopaths being corralled into risking their lives for no tangible gain. There's also more backstory for characters that were totally sidelined in the final film, like Katana, and characters like Killer Croc are given more definition. We'll never know for sure if the original cut would have been better unless WB caves in to fans' demands and released another Director's Cut on DVD, but regardless of the quality, the original would definitely have been a much more intriguing film than the one we ended up with.
